terraform init: Initializes a Terraform working directory by downloading required provider plugins, setting up the backend, and preparing the environment for further Terraform commands
terraform plan: Generates and displays an execution plan, showing what changes Terraform will make to your infrastructure before actually applying them
terraform apply: Executes the actions proposed in the Terraform plan and creates, modifies, or deletes infrastructure resources as required
terraform apply --auto-approve: Applies the Terraform plan without asking for interactive confirmation, automatically creating or modifying resources as defined in the configuration
terraform destroy: Destroys all infrastructure resources managed by Terraform in the current workspace, removing everything defined in the configuration files
terraform fmt: Automatically formats all Terraform configuration files in the current directory to follow standard Terraform style conventions, improving readability and consistency
aws configure: Interactively sets up your AWS CLI credentials and default settings. You will be prompted to enter:AWS Access Key ID, Secret Access Key, Default region name, Default output format
terraform destroy --auto-approve --target=resource_name.label: Destroys only the specified Terraform resource without prompting for confirmation, leaving all other managed resources untouched
terraform workspace list: Displays all Terraform workspaces available in the current working directory, highlighting the currently active workspace
terraform workspace new workspace_name: Creates a new Terraform workspace , allowing you to manage separate state files for different environments (such as dev, test, or prod)
terraform workspace select default: Switches the current Terraform working context to the default workspace, making its state and resources active for subsequent Terraform operations
terraform workspace delete workspace_name: Deletes the specified Terraform workspace, removing its state reference from the current working directory
terraform state list: Lists all resources currently tracked in the Terraform state file for the active workspace
terraform apply -refresh-only: updates Terraform state to match the real infrastructure without creating, modifying, or destroying any resources
terraform taint resource_name: Used to manually mark a resource as “dirty” so Terraform will destroy and recreate it on the next apply, even if the configuration hasn’t changed 
terraform apply --auto-approve -replace="resource_name": Forces Terraform to destroy and recreate a specific resource in a single apply, replacing the deprecated terraform taint
